7c7c2d3f-9e80-4513-8ef3-f775d041f308.text: Chris Drange is a German contemporary artist who is best known for his large-format post-digital portraits and realist oil paintings of modern-day influencers and social media symbols. He was born in 1983 in Köthen (Anhalt), Germany and studied at the International Center of Photography and the Art Students League of New York. He also holds a bachelor’s and a master’s degree in fine arts from the University of Fine Arts in Hamburg. He does not paint his own artworks, but sends sketches made from digital found-objects to an oil painting factory in China, where they are painted by hand on canvas. He has published two photobooks, Hecho en Socialismo and Relics, and has exhibited at various museums and galleries such as the Whitechapel Gallery, London, the Nasher Sculpture Center, Dallas, the UCCA Center for Contemporary Art, Beijing, and the Galerie König, Berlin. He lives and works in both Hamburg and Berlin

24c3510a-f63b-4031-8a54-61f9f08d37c2.text: Eliza Douglas is a US American painter, performer and photographer who lives and works in New York City and Berlin. She is known for her imaginative paintings that combine realism, abstraction and humor, as well as her collaborations with the German artist Anne Imhof. She has also worked as a model for Balenciaga and Vetements. She was born in 1984 and studied at Bard College and Städelschule. Her work has been exhibited at The Whitney Biennial, Museum Folkwang, Schinkel Pavillon, and the Jewish Museum, among others. She is the partner of Anne Imhof and the great-granddaughter of Dorothy Wolff Douglas, a professor of economics at Smith College

f0d877cf-4927-4192-b01a-b643bb3485e4.text: Elmgreen and Dragset are a duo of artists who work at the crossroads of art and architecture, performance and installation. They are Michael Elmgreen, born in Copenhagen, Denmark in 1961, and Ingar Dragset, born in Trondheim, Norway in 1969. They met in Copenhagen in 1994 and started collaborating in 1995. They live and work in Berlin, Germany. They are known for their humorous and subversive works that challenge the conventions of art institutions and public spaces. Some of their well-known projects include Prada Marfa, a replica of a Prada boutique in the middle of the Texan desert, Van Gogh’s Ear, a sculpture of a swimming pool in the shape of an ear at Rockefeller Plaza in New York, and The Collectors, their acclaimed exhibition for the Nordic and Danish Pavilions at the 53rd Venice Biennale in 2009. They have also exhibited at the Whitechapel Gallery, London, the Nasher Sculpture Center, Dallas, the UCCA Center for Contemporary Art, Beijing, and the Palais de Tokyo, Paris, among others
